This research harnesses the extensive resources of the Developing Human Connectome Project to undertake an exhaustive examination of major white matter fibers in the infant brain using Magnetic Resonance Imaging (MRI) data. Our objective was to delineate the developmental trajectories of these crucial neurological structures, thereby contributing to a more nuanced understanding of early brain maturation. We identified and tracked the progression of key white matter structures over a period of infancy, providing novel insights into the dynamic process of early neural connectivity. Our findings have substantial implications for the field of pediatric neuroscience and could potentially support the early detection of developmental disorders. By elucidating these developmental pathways, this study contributes significantly to the ongoing exploration of the human brain's intricate wiring from its earliest stages.
